web_results.snippet: A snail is a shelled gastropod. The name is most often applied to land snails, terrestrial pulmonate gastropod molluscs. However, the common name snail is also used for most of the members of the molluscan class Gastropoda that have a coiled shell that is large enough for the animal to retract completely into.

related_questions.question: Are snails good or bad for you?
related_questions.snippet: In addition to containing significant sources of protein and low amounts of fat, snails are also good sources of iron, calcium, Vitamin A, and a number of other minerals. Vitamin A helps your immune system fight off diseases and strengthens your eyes. It also helps cells in your body grow.

related_questions.question: What is the difference between a slug and a snail?
related_questions.snippet: The main difference between them is that a snail has a shell and a slug does not. Snails and slugs belong to the group of soft-bodied animals called mollusks, which also includes oysters, clams, and squid. Snails and slugs are found throughout the world. Some live on land or in trees.

related_questions.question: What is a snail without a shell called?
related_questions.snippet: Gastropods that lack a conspicuous shell are commonly called slugs rather than snails.

buttons.title: Land snail - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: Lifespan. Most species of land snail are annual, others are known to live 2 or 3 years, but some of the larger species may live over 10 years in the wild. For instance, 10-year old individuals of the Roman snail Helix pomatia are probably not uncommon in natural populations.

buttons.subtitle: Are Snails Poisonous?
buttons.title: Not Poisonous, but Venomous -Dangerous Snails to Avoid!
buttons.snippet: Most snails are harmless to humans, and they are helpful to the environment. However, out of the 40,000 species of snails we know, there are hundreds of snails that can be venomous (not poisonous) and therefore dangerous to humans.
snippet_highlighted_words: Most snails are harmless to humans

buttons.subtitle: Can You Eat Snails?
buttons.title: A Microscopic Look at Snail Jaws | Natural History Museum
buttons.snippet: Snails and slugs have evolved to eat just about everything; they are herbivorous, carnivorous, omnivorous, and detritivorous (eating decaying waste from plants and other animals). There are specialist and generalist species that eat worms, vegetation, rotting vegetation, animal waste, fungus, and other snails.
snippet_highlighted_words: herbivorous, carnivorous, omnivorous, and detritivorous (eating decaying waste from plants and other animals)

buttons.subtitle: How Do Snails Live?
buttons.title: Snail Habitat: Lesson for Kids - Study.com
buttons.snippet: Snails live all over the world in soil (or dirt), sand, trees, under rocks or leaves, and in the rivers, lakes, and oceans. Land snails cannot breathe under water so they must come out when too much water enters their habitat to avoid drowning.

buttons.title: BBC Wales - Nature - Wildlife - Questions and answers
buttons.snippet: They lay their small white eggs in a clump just under the surface of the soil in the late spring or summer. After a few weeks, the eggs hatch and the tiny baby snails emerge - already with their shells! At this stage, their shells are colourless, soft and delicate.

buttons.subtitle: Where Do Snails Live?
buttons.title: Wild About Illinois Land Snails and Slugs!
buttons.snippet: Snails need to seek sheltered places to live, eat and rest. They prefer to live in moist areas and are commonly found under logs, loose bark or coarse woody debris, and in leaf litter on the forest floor. In general, snail populations are greatest in areas that have high soil calcium levels.
snippet_highlighted_words: under logs, loose bark or coarse woody debris, and in leaf litter on the forest floor

buttons.subtitle: Snail Diet
buttons.title: How to Feed a Snail: Diets for Land & Freshwater Snails - wikiHow
buttons.snippet: Feed your land snail juicy fruits like apricots, leafy vegetables like lettuce, sunflower seeds, cooked grains like oatmeal, and rich calcium sources like cuttlebone. Feed your freshwater snail aquatic plants like algae, food debris from your aquarium, blanched vegetables, and calcium sources like eggshells.
snippet_highlighted_words: juicy fruits like apricots, leafy vegetables like lettuce, sunflower seeds, cooked grains like oatmeal, and rich calcium sources like cuttlebone

buttons.subtitle: Snail Predators
buttons.title: Predators & Defenses - Mollusks : Carnegie Museum of Natural History
buttons.snippet: Vertebrate predators of snails and slugs include shrews, mice, squirrels, and other small mammals; salamanders, toads and turtles, including the uncommon Blandings Turtle Emydoidea blandingii; and birds, especially ground-foragers such as thrushes, grouse, blackbirds, and wild turkey.
